Today's Challenge: The Model Showdown

Scenario: You've spent 3 months developing a new neural network architecture. Your colleague improved the old model with better hyperparameters. Both models were tested:

  • Your new model: 87.2% accuracy on 150 test images
  • Improved old model: 85.8% accuracy on 150 test images

Your colleague says: "The difference is only 1.4%. That's probably just noise. We should stick with my improved version of the old model since it's faster to train."

You reply: "But mine IS better. That 1.4% could be real!"

The Million Dollar Questions:

  1. Is the 1.4% difference statistically significant?
  2. What if both models were tested on the same 150 images - does that change the analysis?
  3. How do you prove your model is worth the extra training time?

By the end of this lesson, you'll be able to settle this debate with mathematical rigor

Independent vs Paired Samples

When comparing two groups, the relationship between samples fundamentally changes our analysis approach.

Definition: Independent Samples

Independent samples are two groups where the observations in one group have no relationship to observations in the other group. The samples are drawn separately.

Characteristics:

  • Different subjects/units in each group
  • Sample sizes can be different (n n)
  • No natural pairing between observations

ML Examples:

  • Model A tested on 200 random images, Model B tested on 150 different random images
  • Comparing click-through rates: Group A sees Version 1, Group B sees Version 2
  • Algorithm performance on Mac vs Windows users (different users)

Definition: Paired/Dependent Samples

Paired samples (also called dependent or matched samples) are two measurements on the same subjects/units, or subjects matched in pairs.

Characteristics:

  • Same subjects measured twice (before/after)
  • Or matched pairs of subjects
  • Sample sizes MUST be equal (n = n)
  • Natural pairing between observations

ML Examples:

  • Model A and Model B both tested on the same 200 images
  • User behavior before and after feature deployment (same users)
  • Algorithm performance on matched pairs of similar tasks

Key Insight: Why Paring Matters?

Observations:

  1. If $p$-value of the paired test is smaller than 0.05 while the one of independent test is not:
  • Paired test detected the difference, but independent test didn't.
  • Pairing reduces noise by accounting for subject-to-subject variation.
  1. If p_paired < p_indep:
  • Paired test has a smaller p-value (more powerful).
  • When measurements are correlated, pairing increases statistical power.
  1. If the same results:
  • In this case, both tests give similar results.

The Power of Pairing: When measurements are correlated (same subjects, similar conditions), paired tests:

  1. Remove between-subject variability: We only care about within-subject changes
  2. Increase statistical power: Easier to detect real differences
  3. Require fewer samples: More efficient use of data

Rule of Thumb: If you CAN pair (test on same subjects/units), you SHOULD pair

ML Application Spotlight: Choosing the Right Design

Use INDEPENDENT samples when:

  • Comparing models on different user groups (A/B test with random assignment)
  • Comparing algorithms with different training sets
  • Evaluating models from different time periods
  • Testing demographic differences (Mac vs PC users)

Use PAIRED samples when:

  • Comparing multiple models on the same test set
  • Before/after deployment comparisons (same users)
  • Cross-validation folds (same data, different splits)
  • Ablation studies (model with/without feature X on same data)

Example Decision:

BAD: Model A on 100 cat images, Model B on 100 dog images Biased comparison!

GOOD: Both models on the same 100 images (50 cats, 50 dogs) Fair paired comparison

Independent Samples - Comparing Two Means

The Two-Sample t-Test for Independent Samples

When comparing means from two independent groups, we need to account for variability in both groups.

Key Question: Are the population variances equal?

  • If = Use pooled variance (Student's t-test)
  • If Use Welch's t-test (separate variances)

Student's t-Test (Equal Variances Assumed)

Hypotheses:

  • H: = (or equivalently, - = 0)
  • H: (two-tailed), or > (right), or < (left)

Test Statistic:

$$t = \frac{(\bar{X}_1 - \bar{X}_2))} {s_p \times \sqrt{1/n_1 + 1/n_2}}$$

Pooled Standard Deviation:

$$s_p = \sqrt{\frac{(n_1 - 1)s_1^2 + (n_2 - 1)s_2^2} {n_1 + n_2 - 2}}$$

Degrees of Freedom: $df = n_1 + n_2 - 2$

Distribution: t-distribution with (n + n - 2) degrees of freedom

When to use: When variances are approximately equal (check with F-test or Levene's test)

Welch's t-Test (Unequal Variances)

Test Statistic:

$$t = \frac{(\bar{X_1} - \bar{X_2})}{\sqrt{(s_1^2/n_1 + s_2^2/n_2)}}$$

Welch-Satterthwaite Degrees of Freedom:

$$df = \frac{(s_1^2/n_1 + s_2^2/n_2)^2}{(s_1^2/n_1)^2/(n_1-1) + (s_2^2/n_2)^2/(n_2-1)}$$

When to use: Default choice when you're unsure about variance equality (more robust)

Note: When variances are equal, Welch's test performs similarly to Student's t-test. When unequal, Welch's is more accurate

Key Insight: When to Use Which Test

Practical Rule: Use Welch's t-test by default!

  • If variances are actually equal Welch performs just as well as Student's
  • If variances differ Welch is more accurate, Student's can be misleading
  • Welch's is more robust and doesn't require variance equality assumption

In Python:

  • stats.ttest_ind(group1, group2, equal_var=True) Student's t-test (pooled)
  • stats.ttest_ind(group1, group2, equal_var=False) Welch's t-test (DEFAULT!)

The Problem with $p$-Value Alone:

P-value tells you: "Is there a statistically significant difference?"

  • $p < 0.05$ Difference is unlikely due to chance
  • But says NOTHING about how big or important the difference is.

That's why we need effect size analysis.

Effect size tells you: "How BIG is the difference?"

  • Is it tiny but statistically significant? (large sample)
  • Is it huge but not significant? (small sample)
  • Does it matter in practice?

Note: Statistical significance Practical significance

A difference can be:

  • Statistically significant but trivially small (large $n$)
  • Large and important but not significant (small $n$)

So, always report: p-value (Is it real?), effect size (How big is it?), CI (What's the range?)

Key Insight: Effect Size

With large samples (n=10,000):

  • Even tiny differences (1 point) are statistically significant
  • But they may not matter in practice!

With small samples (n=20):

  • Even large differences (15 points) may not be significant
  • But they could be very important in practice

SOLUTION: Always report EFFECT SIZE alongside p-values

Definition: Effect Size for Comparing Means

Cohen's $d$ is a STANDARDIZED measure of the difference between two means.

It answers: "How many standard deviations apart are the two groups?"

Intuition: Think of it as converting the difference to a common scale:

  • Like converting to "standard drink units" to compare alcohol content
  • Allows comparison across different units/scales
  • A "universal ruler" for effect sizes

Formula:

$$d = \frac{\bar{X}_1 - \bar{X}_2}{s_{pooled}}$$

where $s_{pooled} = \sqrt{\frac{(n_1-1)s_1^2 + (n_2-1)s_2^2}{n_1 + n_2 - 2}}$

Interpretation:

  • |d| = 0.0 to 0.2 Negligible effect
  • |d| = 0.2 to 0.5 Small effect
  • |d| = 0.5 to 0.8 Medium effect
  • |d| = 0.8+ Large effect

Remark: Context matters - a "small" effect in one domain might be huge in another.

Key Properties:

  • Unit-free (standardized)
  • Independent of sample size
  • Can compare across different studies/measurements
  • Can be positive or negative (direction of difference)

# Cohen's d (effect size)
pooled_std_for_d = np.sqrt(((n1-1)*s1**2 + (n2-1)*s2**2) / (n1 + n2 - 2))
cohens_d = (x2_bar - x1_bar) / pooled_std_for_d

print(f"Cohen's d = (x_ViT - x_CNN) / pooled_std")
print(f"          = ({x2_bar:.2f} - {x1_bar:.2f}) / {pooled_std_for_d:.2f}")
print(f"          = {cohens_d:.4f}")

# Interpret Cohen's d
if abs(cohens_d) < 0.2:
    interpretation = "NEGLIGIBLE"
elif abs(cohens_d) < 0.5:
    interpretation = "SMALL"
elif abs(cohens_d) < 0.8:
    interpretation = "MEDIUM"
else:
    interpretation = "LARGE"


print(f"\nEffect Size Interpretation: {interpretation}")

Paired Samples - Paired $t$-Test

When samples are paired, we don't compare groups directly. Instead, we:

  1. Calculate the difference for each pair: $d_i = x_{2_i} - x_{1_i}$
  2. Test if the mean difference is zero: H: $\mu_d = 0$

This transforms a two-sample problem into a one-sample problem.

Paired t-Test Formula

Hypotheses:

  • $H_0: \mu_d = 0$ (no difference between paired measurements)
  • $H_1$: $\mu_d 0$ (two-tailed), or $\mu_d > 0$ (right), or $\mu_d < 0$ (left)

Test Statistic:

$$t = \frac{\bar{d}}{(s_d / \sqrt{n})}$$

Where:

  • $\bar{d}$ = mean of differences
  • $s_d$ = standard deviation of differences
  • $n$ = number of pairs

Degrees of Freedom: df = n - 1 (number of pairs minus 1)

Distribution: t-distribution with (n-1) degrees of freedom

Calculated Example: Model Performance Before and After Optimization

Context: You've optimized your image classification model (quantization + pruning). You want to know if the optimization affected accuracy.

Experiment Design:

  • Selected 25 diverse test images
  • Tested BOTH original and optimized models on the SAME images
  • Recorded binary accuracy (correct=1, incorrect=0) for each image

Objectives:
  • Determine if optimization significantly changed accuracy
  • Quantify the average difference
  • Use paired analysis to account for image difficulty

In[26]:
# Generate realistic paired data
np.random.seed(456)

n_images = 25

# Image difficulty (latent variable - not observed)
image_difficulty = np.random.uniform(0, 1, n_images)

# Original model accuracy (depends on difficulty)
# Easier images have higher probability of being correct
prob_original = 0.85 - 0.4 * image_difficulty
original_correct = (np.random.random(n_images) < prob_original).astype(int)

# Optimized model is slightly worse (lost ~3% accuracy on average)
prob_optimized = prob_original - 0.03
optimized_correct = (np.random.random(n_images) < prob_optimized).astype(int)

# Calculate differences
differences = optimized_correct - original_correct

print(f"Number of images: {n_images}")
print(f"Original model accuracy: {original_correct.mean()*100:.1f}%")
print(f"Optimized model accuracy: {optimized_correct.mean()*100:.1f}%")
print(f"Mean difference: {differences.mean():.4f}")

Number of images: 25
Original model accuracy: 68.0%
Optimized model accuracy: 72.0%
Mean difference: 0.0400

Comparing Proportions

Two-Sample Z-Test for Proportions

Use Case: Comparing success rates between two groups (e.g., A/B test conversion rates)

Hypotheses:

  • H: p = p (proportions are equal)
  • H: p p (two-tailed), or p > p, or p < p

Test Statistic:

$$z = \frac{\hat{p}_1 - \hat{p}_2} {\sqrt{\hat{p}(1-\hat{p})(1/n_1 + 1/n_2)}}$$

Pooled Proportion:

$$\hat{p} = (x_1 + x_2) / (n_1 + n_2)$$

Assumptions:

  • np 10, n(1-p) 10
  • np 10, n(1-p) 10
  • Independent samples

Calculated Example: A/B Test for Proportions

TechShop, an e-commerce website, wants to test if a new landing page design improves the conversion rate (percentage of visitors who add items to cart).

Experiment:

  • Version A (Control): Current design
  • Version B (New): Redesigned page with prominent "Add to Cart" button
  • Random assignment: 1,000 visitors to each version

Data collected:

  1. Version A (Control):
  • Visitors: $n_A = 1,000$
  • Conversions: $x_A = 120$
  • Conversion rate: $\hat{p}_A = 12.0%$
  1. Version B (New):
  • Visitors: $n_B = 1,200$
  • Conversions: $x_B = 165$
  • Conversion rate: $\hat{p}_B = 13.75%$
  1. Observed difference: 13.75% - 12.0% = 1.75 percentage points

Question: Does the new design (Version B) have a significantly higher conversion rate than the current design (Version A)?

Hypotheses:

  • $H_0: p_A = p_B$ (no difference in conversion rates)
  • $H_1: p_B > p_A$ (Version B has higher conversion rate)
  • Significance level: $\alpha = 0.05$

Your Task:

  1. Test if the difference is statistically significant
  2. Calculate and interpret the effect size
  3. Provide a recommendation: Should TechShop deploy Version B?

In[35]:
# Manual calculation
pooled_p = (conversions_a + conversions_b) / (n_a + n_b)
se = np.sqrt(pooled_p * (1 - pooled_p) * (1/n_a + 1/n_b))
z_stat = (p_b - p_a) / se
p_value = 2 * (1 - stats.norm.cdf(abs(z_stat)))

print(f"\nPooled proportion: {pooled_p:.4f}")
print(f"Standard error: {se:.4f}")
print(f"Z-statistic: {z_stat:.4f}")
print(f"P-value: {p_value:.6f}")

Comparing Variances

F-Test for Equality of Variances

Use Case: Testing if two populations have equal variances (before choosing t-test type)

Hypotheses:

  • H: = (variances are equal)
  • H: (variances differ)

Test Statistic:

$$F = s_1^2 / s_2^2 \text{ (where } s_1^2 \geq s_2^2)$$

Distribution: $F$-distribution with $(n-1, n-1)$ degrees of freedom

Warning: F-test is sensitive to non-normality. Modern practice: use Welch's t-test by default instead of testing variances first!

What is $F$-distribution?

Definition: F-Distribution

The F-distribution is the distribution of the ratio of two independent chi-square random variables, each divided by its degrees of freedom.

If $\chi_1^2 \sim \chi^2(df_1)$ and $\chi_2^2 \sim \chi^2(df_2)$ are independent

Then:

$$F = \frac{\chi_1^2 / df_1}{\chi_2^2 / df_2} \sim F(df_1, df_2)$$

Key Properties

  1. RANGE:
  • $F \geq 0$ (always non-negative)
  • $F \in [0, \infty)$
  • Cannot be negative (it's a ratio of variances)
  1. SHAPE:
  • Right-skewed (positive skew)
  • Asymmetric distribution
  • Long right tail
  • Mode < Median < Mean
  1. PARAMETERS:
  • Completely determined by $df_1$ and $df_2$
  • Different df different distribution shape
  1. MEAN:
  • $E[F] = df_2 / (df_2 - 2)$ for $df_2 > 2$
  • Approaches 1 as $df_2 \rightarrow \infty$
  • Undefined if $df_2 \leq 2$
  1. VARIANCE:
  • $Var[F] = 2df_2^2(df_1 + df_2 - 2) / [df_1(df_2-2)^2(df_2-4)]$ for $df_2 > 4$
  • Decreases as $df$ increase
  • High variability with small $df$
  1. RELATIONSHIP TO OTHER DISTRIBUTIONS:
  • If $t \sim t(df)$, then $t^2 \sim F(1, df)$
  • As $df_1, df_2 \rightarrow \infty$, $F$ Normal distribution (by CLT)
  • $F(df_1, df_2) = 1 / F(df_2, df_1)$ in distribution

Calculated Examples: Comparing Model Prediction Variability

A machine learning team has developed two regression models (Model A and Model B) to predict house prices. Both models achieve similar average accuracy, but the team wants to know if they have similar CONSISTENCY in their predictions.

Why this matters:

  • A model with lower variance is more reliable and predictable
  • High variance means inconsistent predictions (some very good, some very bad)
  • For deployment, consistency is often as important as average accuracy

Data Collected:

Both models tested on their prediction errors (predicted - actual):

  1. Model A (Standard algorithm):
  • Sample size: n = 25 houses
  • Mean error: x = 2,500 dollars
  • Standard deviation: s = 12,000 dollars
  • Variance: s = 144,000,000 dollars
  1. Model B (New ensemble method):
  • Sample size: n = 30 houses
  • Mean error: x = 2,200 dollars
  • Standard deviation: s = 8,500 dollars
  • Variance: s = 72,250,000 dollars

Task: Test whether the two models have equal variance in their prediction errors.

Hypotheses:

  • $H_0: \sigma_1^2 = \sigma_2^2$ (equal variances - models equally consistent)
  • $H_1: \sigma_1^2 \neq \sigma_2^2$ (unequal variances - different consistency)
  • Test type: TWO-TAILED
  • Significance level: $\alpha = 0.05$

# Critical values for two-tailed test
F_critical_upper = stats.f.ppf(1 - alpha/2, df1, df2)
F_critical_lower = stats.f.ppf(alpha/2, df1, df2)

For a two-tailed test at  = {alpha}:
   We split  into two tails: /2 = {alpha/2} in each tail
   We reject H if F is too large OR too small

Upper critical value (right tail):
  F_upper = F/(df, df)
          = F.({df1}, {df2})
          = {F_critical_upper:.6f}

Lower critical value (left tail):
  F_lower = F/(df, df)
          = F.({df1}, {df2})
          = {F_critical_lower:.6f}

Decision rule:
  Reject H if: F < {F_critical_lower:.4f} OR F > {F_critical_upper:.4f}
  Fail to reject H if: {F_critical_lower:.4f}  F  {F_critical_upper:.4f}
""")

# Calculate p-value for two-tailed test
# Since F > 1, we're in the right tail
p_upper = 1 - stats.f.cdf(F_stat, df1, df2)
p_lower = stats.f.cdf(F_stat, df1, df2)
p_value = 2 * min(p_upper, p_lower)  # Two-tailed

print(f"""
Our observed F = {F_stat:.6f} is greater than 1, so it's in the right tail.

Right tail probability:
  P(F > {F_stat:.4f}) = {p_upper:.6f}

For two-tailed test:
  p-value = 2  min(P(F > {F_stat:.4f}), P(F < {F_stat:.4f}))
          = 2  {min(p_upper, p_lower):.6f}
          = {p_value:.6f}

Interpretation:
  If the variances were truly equal, there's a {p_value*100:.2f}% chance of
  observing a variance ratio this extreme or more extreme.
""")

Our observed F = 1.993080 is greater than 1, so it's in the right tail.

Right tail probability:
  P(F > 1.9931) = 0.038801

For two-tailed test:
  p-value = 2  min(P(F > 1.9931), P(F < 1.9931))
          = 2  0.038801
          = 0.077601

Practical implications:
   Both models have similar prediction consistency
   Cannot confidently claim one model is more reliable than the other
   Other factors (accuracy, interpretability, speed) should guide decision

Recommendation:
   Consider other metrics for model selection
   May need more data to detect variance differences
   Could test on larger sample to increase statistical power
"""

print(interpretation)

Key Insights: F-Test

  1. F-TEST is for comparing VARIANCES, not means
  • Tests if two populations have equal variability
  • Very sensitive to non-normality assumption
  1. F-STATISTIC is a RATIO of variances
  • F = s / s (larger variance in numerator)
  • F 1 always (by convention)
  • F close to 1 similar variances
  • F far from 1 different variances
  1. F-DISTRIBUTION has TWO degrees of freedom
  • df (numerator) and df (denominator)
  • Order matters! F(5,20) F(20,5)
  1. PRACTICAL IMPORTANCE
  • In ML: Consistency often as important as accuracy
  • Lower variance = More reliable predictions
  • Easier to set confidence intervals and make guarantees

Python Reference

Python Reference Guide: Two-Sample Tests

INDEPENDENT SAMPLES - MEANS (t-test)
from scipy import stats

# Welch's t-test (DEFAULT - unequal variances assumed)
t_stat, p_value = stats.ttest_ind(group1, group2, equal_var=False)

# Student's t-test (equal variances assumed)
t_stat, p_value = stats.ttest_ind(group1, group2, equal_var=True)

# One-sided p-value
p_right = p_value / 2 if t_stat > 0 else 1 - p_value/2
p_left = p_value / 2 if t_stat < 0 else 1 - p_value/2
PAIRED SAMPLES - MEANS (paired t-test)
from scipy import stats

# Paired t-test
t_stat, p_value = stats.ttest_rel(after, before)

# Equivalent: one-sample test on differences
differences = after - before
t_stat, p_value = stats.ttest_1samp(differences, 0)
TWO PROPORTIONS (z-test)
from statsmodels.stats.proportion import proportions_ztest

# counts: [successes in group1, successes in group2]
# nobs: [total in group1, total in group2]
z_stat, p_value = proportions_ztest(counts, nobs, alternative='two-sided')
# alternative can be 'two-sided', 'larger', or 'smaller'
EQUALITY OF VARIANCES
from scipy import stats

# Levene's test (robust to non-normality)
stat, p_value = stats.levene(group1, group2)

# F-test (sensitive to non-normality)
f_stat = np.var(group1, ddof=1) / np.var(group2, ddof=1)
df1, df2 = len(group1)-1, len(group2)-1
p_value = 2 * min(stats.f.cdf(f_stat, df1, df2), 
                  1 - stats.f.cdf(f_stat, df1, df2))
EFFECT SIZE (Cohen's d)
def cohens_d(group1, group2):
    n1, n2 = len(group1), len(group2)
    var1, var2 = np.var(group1, ddof=1), np.var(group2, ddof=1)
    pooled_std = np.sqrt(((n1-1)*var1 + (n2-1)*var2) / (n1+n2-2))
    return (np.mean(group1) - np.mean(group2)) / pooled_std

# For paired samples
def cohens_d_paired(differences):
    return np.mean(differences) / np.std(differences, ddof=1)
CONFIDENCE INTERVALS
from scipy import stats

# For difference of means (independent)
diff = np.mean(group1) - np.mean(group2)
se = np.sqrt(np.var(group1,ddof=1)/len(group1) + np.var(group2,ddof=1)/len(group2))
df = len(group1) + len(group2) - 2
ci = stats.t.interval(0.95, df, loc=diff, scale=se)

# For paired differences
diff_mean = np.mean(differences)
diff_se = stats.sem(differences)
df = len(differences) - 1
ci = stats.t.interval(0.95, df, loc=diff_mean, scale=diff_se)

Key Takeaways

Key Takeaways

  1. Pairing vs Independence: Paired tests are more powerful when data is naturally paired (same subjects, matched conditions)
  2. Welch's t-test: Use by default for independent samples (robust to unequal variances)
  3. Paired t-test: Transform to one-sample problem on differences
  4. Effect Size Matters: Statistical significance practical significance
  5. Experimental Design: Choice of paired vs independent affects power and validity
